00:00:27.687 --> 00:00:32.070
PROFESSOR: So we had a
big lecture last time

00:00:32.070 --> 00:00:39.720
on perfect insurance and
implications for targeting,

00:00:39.720 --> 00:00:44.290
and policy, and evaluations.

00:00:44.290 --> 00:00:46.420
There is a series
of lectures now

00:00:46.420 --> 00:00:52.120
that have to do with working
off of that basic risk sharing

00:00:52.120 --> 00:00:53.500
framework.

00:00:53.500 --> 00:00:56.770
Today we're going to talk about
the implications for what we

00:00:56.770 --> 00:00:59.290
should see in rates of return.

00:00:59.290 --> 00:01:01.420
And then next class,
we're going to talk

00:01:01.420 --> 00:01:09.460
about alternative models of what
we might see in the consumption

00:01:09.460 --> 00:01:12.118
data.

00:01:12.118 --> 00:01:13.660
And then the lecture
after that we're

00:01:13.660 --> 00:01:17.260
going to return to the
perfect market model

00:01:17.260 --> 00:01:19.910
and think about labor supply.

00:01:19.910 --> 00:01:22.400
And then finally, we're going
to get to explicit obstacles

00:01:22.400 --> 00:01:23.270
to trade.

00:01:23.270 --> 00:01:26.810
I must say that rather
than put off the obstacles,

00:01:26.810 --> 00:01:29.630
we've been noting
and even talking

00:01:29.630 --> 00:01:32.780
about alternative
models along the way.

00:01:35.660 --> 00:01:37.490
Because these
benchmarks are sometimes

00:01:37.490 --> 00:01:40.010
rejected and you're going to
see that a bit today as well.

00:01:42.550 --> 00:01:47.940
So this perfect market
standard within villages

00:01:47.940 --> 00:01:51.570
that has to do with
relatives and friends

00:01:51.570 --> 00:01:54.210
interacting with each
other has implications

00:01:54.210 --> 00:01:56.520
for how you adjust for risk.

00:01:56.520 --> 00:01:59.860
And we're going to do
that with a vengeance.

00:01:59.860 --> 00:02:02.920
But it will turn
out that it does--

00:02:02.920 --> 00:02:05.530
that framework allows us
to distinguish aggregate

00:02:05.530 --> 00:02:07.790
from idiosyncratic risk.

00:02:07.790 --> 00:02:11.020
And the idiosyncratic
risk should not

00:02:11.020 --> 00:02:16.800
be showing up in rates of
return, but it does at the end.

00:02:19.380 --> 00:02:22.050
And then I'll say a few
words about what else

00:02:22.050 --> 00:02:24.930
we know about the
tie data in terms

00:02:24.930 --> 00:02:28.440
of the decomposition
of volatility

00:02:28.440 --> 00:02:31.710
linking back to a
paper we saw the very

00:02:31.710 --> 00:02:39.560
first lecture on quantifying
the growth rates by sector.

00:02:39.560 --> 00:02:42.220
But we're going to
do it by wealth.

00:02:42.220 --> 00:02:45.490
At least I'll say a
few words about it.

00:02:45.490 --> 00:02:51.360
And then I'm going to toward the
end of the class sort of return

00:02:51.360 --> 00:02:53.880
to this idea that
either things aren't

00:02:53.880 --> 00:02:57.080
perfect and/or people
are making mistakes.

00:02:57.080 --> 00:03:02.700
And we'll do that in
some unusual contexts,

00:03:02.700 --> 00:03:05.550
one that has to do
with data from Sweden,

00:03:05.550 --> 00:03:07.860
an unusually rich
database from Sweden,

00:03:07.860 --> 00:03:12.750
and another that has to
do with the US airlines.

00:03:12.750 --> 00:03:14.850
But the basic frameworks
that are getting

00:03:14.850 --> 00:03:18.330
used, whether in the
developing context, or Sweden,

00:03:18.330 --> 00:03:22.030
or US airlines, are
basically all the same.

00:03:22.030 --> 00:03:23.970
So there is a strong
complementarity

00:03:23.970 --> 00:03:26.020
across these papers.

00:03:26.020 --> 00:03:31.800
This paper with Chris has
been in the works for a while.

00:03:31.800 --> 00:03:36.370
But we are now able to use you
know 13 years of monthly data.

00:03:36.370 --> 00:03:41.890
So we are doing
better than before.

00:03:41.890 --> 00:03:46.230
So we want to talk about risk
and return of productive assets

00:03:46.230 --> 00:03:47.520
in developing countries.

00:03:50.390 --> 00:03:53.300
We already looked at some
of the slides showing

00:03:53.300 --> 00:03:57.530
how rates of return differ a
lot across different households,

00:03:57.530 --> 00:04:01.750
differ in large part
by wealth and how

00:04:01.750 --> 00:04:06.070
poor people have relatively
high rates of return.

00:04:06.070 --> 00:04:07.090
And they're saving.

00:04:07.090 --> 00:04:11.050
And they're accumulating
assets and so on.

00:04:15.560 --> 00:04:19.160
Another way people look at
rates of return is to say,

00:04:19.160 --> 00:04:24.540
you know, well, some people
are more talented than others.

00:04:24.540 --> 00:04:26.840
So if we look at
rates of return,

00:04:26.840 --> 00:04:30.380
we get some notion of
underlying productivity

00:04:30.380 --> 00:04:32.900
as in TFP and so on.

00:04:32.900 --> 00:04:35.960
We've had many
lectures about TFP

00:04:35.960 --> 00:04:39.500
and coefficients in
front multiplying

00:04:39.500 --> 00:04:42.890
in front of production
functions and so on.

00:04:42.890 --> 00:04:44.750
But correct me if I'm wrong.

00:04:44.750 --> 00:04:50.390
Nowhere in any of that stuff
did we ever adjust for risk.

00:04:50.390 --> 00:04:54.220
So what's the intuition
for adjusting for risk?

00:04:54.220 --> 00:05:00.670
Well, if you want to look at
compensating differentials,

00:05:00.670 --> 00:05:03.370
the higher the risk of a
project, the higher the rate

00:05:03.370 --> 00:05:05.020
of return ought to be.

00:05:05.020 --> 00:05:08.300
Other things equal to
compensate for that risk.

00:05:08.300 --> 00:05:11.440
You know, like junk
bonds have higher yields

00:05:11.440 --> 00:05:14.360
and so on and so forth.

00:05:14.360 --> 00:05:16.720
So maybe these guys with
seemingly very high rates

00:05:16.720 --> 00:05:21.370
of return actually are
just doing risky things.

00:05:21.370 --> 00:05:24.720
And indeed, if enough of them
do risky things and on average

00:05:24.720 --> 00:05:26.240
some of them succeed
and maybe that

00:05:26.240 --> 00:05:27.960
would generate the
high rate of return.

00:05:27.960 --> 00:05:32.655
So we really need to think
about how to measure the risk.

00:05:37.620 --> 00:05:39.450
And we're going to
rely on finance theory.

00:05:39.450 --> 00:05:46.080
But I'll be very
careful to sort of build

00:05:46.080 --> 00:05:48.240
into it the economic models.

00:05:48.240 --> 00:05:52.110
You may learn a little bit of
finance jargon along the way.

00:05:52.110 --> 00:05:54.180
But I'm not going
to start with that.

00:05:54.180 --> 00:05:56.850
I'll get you up to speed.

00:05:56.850 --> 00:06:00.090
It's really not that hard when
you look at the equations.

00:06:05.200 --> 00:06:08.030
OK, so what do we find?

00:06:13.220 --> 00:06:17.905
We do find that higher
risk is associated

00:06:17.905 --> 00:06:19.030
with higher rate of return.

00:06:21.670 --> 00:06:24.070
But the risk that we're
going to be concentrating on

00:06:24.070 --> 00:06:26.860
in the model is not
idiosyncratic risk.

00:06:26.860 --> 00:06:31.110
It's village level risk.

00:06:31.110 --> 00:06:35.540
So when you think about
households together pooling

00:06:35.540 --> 00:06:39.800
resources, as in a
risk sharing syndicate,

00:06:39.800 --> 00:06:43.100
they would care about say
aggregate consumption should

00:06:43.100 --> 00:06:45.440
move individual consumption.

00:06:45.440 --> 00:06:48.470
And idiosyncratic
income shock should not

00:06:48.470 --> 00:06:51.270
have an influence
on consumption.

00:06:51.270 --> 00:06:53.315
So when is something
really valuable?

00:06:55.840 --> 00:06:57.650
A project is
valuable when it has

00:06:57.650 --> 00:07:01.070
a return, which is negatively
correlated with the village

00:07:01.070 --> 00:07:02.330
average return.

00:07:02.330 --> 00:07:05.930
So that the resources
come in when you need it.

00:07:05.930 --> 00:07:09.890
So the quote market,
the way the finance guys

00:07:09.890 --> 00:07:11.615
would use it, for
us is the village.

00:07:17.410 --> 00:07:24.110
And indeed, the more a household
has a return on its projects

00:07:24.110 --> 00:07:27.410
that are correlated with
the village average return,

00:07:27.410 --> 00:07:31.850
the higher is going to be the
measured expected or average

00:07:31.850 --> 00:07:33.505
return on that
household's assets.

00:07:36.170 --> 00:07:40.140
And we have all kinds of ways
of adjusting for human capital

00:07:40.140 --> 00:07:43.990
and so on, which I'll get into.

00:07:43.990 --> 00:07:45.790
As I said though,
it does in the end

00:07:45.790 --> 00:07:48.940
leave some idiosyncratic risk.

00:07:48.940 --> 00:07:51.865
And that's also generating
higher expected returns.

00:07:56.070 --> 00:08:00.260
Aggregate and idiosyncratic
risk is negatively

00:08:00.260 --> 00:08:02.940
correlated with age.

00:08:02.940 --> 00:08:07.250
So the older a household
head basically,

00:08:07.250 --> 00:08:12.130
the quote, less risky
things that they're doing.

00:08:12.130 --> 00:08:15.020
But both in the idiosyncratic
and aggregate sense

00:08:15.020 --> 00:08:19.300
they tend to do things which are
less correlated with a village

00:08:19.300 --> 00:08:22.630
average.

00:08:22.630 --> 00:08:24.040
It's negative with wealth.

00:08:24.040 --> 00:08:32.260
Meaning the lower is wealth, the
higher both the idiosyncratic

00:08:32.260 --> 00:08:33.460
and aggregate.

00:08:33.460 --> 00:08:36.970
So this gets us into
poor people and how

00:08:36.970 --> 00:08:39.549
exposed are they to risk?

00:08:39.549 --> 00:08:43.610
We've seen a bit of that
already in risk and return

00:08:43.610 --> 00:08:47.120
in village India that there
are some landless laborers

00:08:47.120 --> 00:08:50.960
and labor income that tends to
move consumption around more.

00:08:50.960 --> 00:08:54.950
This is a bit different way
of measuring it in the sense

00:08:54.950 --> 00:08:58.160
that we're not going to look so
much at the consumption data.

00:08:58.160 --> 00:09:01.760
We're going to assume everyone
is in this risk sharing

00:09:01.760 --> 00:09:02.360
syndicate.

00:09:02.360 --> 00:09:04.040
But we turn around
and see what is

00:09:04.040 --> 00:09:06.360
reflected in rates of return.

00:09:09.120 --> 00:09:11.580
And in particular,
relatively poor people

00:09:11.580 --> 00:09:14.680
are more exposed to risk.

00:09:14.680 --> 00:09:16.950
But it's not just their
own idiosyncratic risk.

00:09:16.950 --> 00:09:18.930
It's the aggregate risk.

00:09:31.540 --> 00:09:36.390
And there is a little bit
of role for education.

00:09:36.390 --> 00:09:37.940
But it's kind of problematic.

00:09:37.940 --> 00:09:40.370
And there's some selection
bias that I might

00:09:40.370 --> 00:09:41.600
talk about when we get there.

00:09:44.240 --> 00:09:48.080
And then this is
maybe the punch line.

00:09:48.080 --> 00:09:50.700
If you want to
think about talent,

00:09:50.700 --> 00:09:55.510
then you want to adjust
for all sources of risk.

00:09:55.510 --> 00:09:58.200
And when we do that, we
find who are seemingly

00:09:58.200 --> 00:10:01.260
the really productive
people in the village.

00:10:01.260 --> 00:10:03.870
And all of a sudden, it's
the higher wealth people

00:10:03.870 --> 00:10:07.440
who have the higher risk
adjusted rate of return

00:10:07.440 --> 00:10:11.050
and female headed households.

00:10:11.050 --> 00:10:14.410
So relatively wealthy
females actually

00:10:14.410 --> 00:10:17.690
dominate in terms of getting
a higher rate of return.

00:10:17.690 --> 00:10:20.330
So we have a basic model.

00:10:20.330 --> 00:10:27.220
They're going to be j households
and l production activities.

00:10:27.220 --> 00:10:32.290
Each activity utilizes
capital as an input.

00:10:32.290 --> 00:10:36.700
And let's simplify and
say all these technologies

00:10:36.700 --> 00:10:39.790
produce the same thing,
consumption goods.

00:10:39.790 --> 00:10:43.960
And we'll simplify further and
assume all the technologies are

00:10:43.960 --> 00:10:45.080
linear.

00:10:45.080 --> 00:10:45.785
Yeah, Matt.

00:10:45.785 --> 00:10:47.160
AUDIENCE: Can I
just actually ask

00:10:47.160 --> 00:10:48.868
a couple of things
about previous slides?

00:10:48.868 --> 00:10:53.400
So are we assuming there's
no sharing between them?

00:10:57.450 --> 00:10:59.370
PROFESSOR: So we
are again, going

00:10:59.370 --> 00:11:05.090
to take a stand on our baseline.

00:11:05.090 --> 00:11:07.180
And it's actually
going to be all four

00:11:07.180 --> 00:11:10.630
villages in a province,
not just a single village.

00:11:10.630 --> 00:11:13.370
But then we go back and check
for villages individually.

00:11:13.370 --> 00:11:18.160
And we actually go back further
and look one network at a time.

00:11:18.160 --> 00:11:19.960
The basic results don't change.

00:11:19.960 --> 00:11:21.360
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:11:21.360 --> 00:11:24.580
Another thing which I
don't really understand

00:11:24.580 --> 00:11:28.850
is when we have this
result that returns

00:11:28.850 --> 00:11:31.155
risk adjusted returns
are lower for those

00:11:31.155 --> 00:11:33.430
with lower [INAUDIBLE].

00:11:33.430 --> 00:11:36.410
How do we think about
in terms of one story's

00:11:36.410 --> 00:11:38.370
that the people with
low initial wealth,

00:11:38.370 --> 00:11:41.250
they're very productive
people amongst them.

00:11:41.250 --> 00:11:44.680
But [INAUDIBLE] get sufficient
size of their business.

00:11:44.680 --> 00:11:48.430
So their marginal returns
might be really high.

00:11:48.430 --> 00:11:50.580
And the average returns
as well, depending on--

00:11:50.580 --> 00:11:52.080
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
so this paper isn't

00:11:52.080 --> 00:11:53.288
going to help much with that.

00:11:53.288 --> 00:11:55.570
Because we're going to
assume linear technologies.

00:11:55.570 --> 00:11:58.058
And margins are going
to be equal to averages.

00:11:58.058 --> 00:11:58.600
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:12:04.840 --> 00:12:06.670
PROFESSOR: And more
generally, you know,

00:12:06.670 --> 00:12:08.860
wealth is clearly an
endogenous variable.

00:12:08.860 --> 00:12:12.710
So we're not saying high wealth
is causing people to have--

00:12:12.710 --> 00:12:15.010
I mean, it's more likely
the other way around.

00:12:15.010 --> 00:12:17.530
But yeah, we've gone
through a series of models

00:12:17.530 --> 00:12:20.080
where wealth helps
overcome constraints.

00:12:20.080 --> 00:12:23.760
The first four lectures
were like that.

00:12:23.760 --> 00:12:27.330
So in a way, this is another
fact finding mission.

00:12:27.330 --> 00:12:29.040
But it's not just
data summaries.

00:12:29.040 --> 00:12:32.220
It's looking at the data
through the lens of the model.

00:12:32.220 --> 00:12:38.130
And you have to make some
assumptions to do that.

00:12:38.130 --> 00:12:44.380
OK, so we have j
production activities.

00:12:44.380 --> 00:12:46.030
We're going to start
the economy off

00:12:46.030 --> 00:12:48.880
with some aggregate wealth, w.

00:12:48.880 --> 00:12:53.440
And those are basically
the projects, the assets,

00:12:53.440 --> 00:12:56.970
or the trees if you like.

00:12:56.970 --> 00:12:58.980
And those projects
are going to have

00:12:58.980 --> 00:13:02.160
rates of return, the fruit.

00:13:02.160 --> 00:13:04.110
So at the beginning
of the period,

00:13:04.110 --> 00:13:07.470
the total sort of
wealth available

00:13:07.470 --> 00:13:09.570
is the sum of the
trees and the fruit.

00:13:09.570 --> 00:13:14.040
So this is a standard kind
of solo reversible capital

00:13:14.040 --> 00:13:18.630
assumption that the assets
can basically be sold.

00:13:18.630 --> 00:13:20.100
There's no irreversibility.

00:13:20.100 --> 00:13:22.800
You can convert them into
consumption if you choose to.

00:13:26.060 --> 00:13:29.360
So we're going to
have a social planner

00:13:29.360 --> 00:13:33.560
sort of directing
the show, which

00:13:33.560 --> 00:13:38.330
is not to say this might not
decentralize in some way.

00:13:38.330 --> 00:13:42.240
That said, I want to
emphasize it's not

00:13:42.240 --> 00:13:47.130
like finance in the sense that
people participate on the New

00:13:47.130 --> 00:13:49.440
York Stock Exchange or
the financial markets,

00:13:49.440 --> 00:13:51.750
and they're buying
and selling stocks.

00:13:51.750 --> 00:13:54.630
We don't even have the data
of all these capital goods.

00:13:54.630 --> 00:13:57.850
That's not the mechanism.

00:13:57.850 --> 00:14:02.040
This planner's problem may
be decentralized in some way.

00:14:02.040 --> 00:14:03.960
But it's just much
more straightforward,

00:14:03.960 --> 00:14:05.910
just like when we
did the risk sharing

00:14:05.910 --> 00:14:07.950
stuff not to
necessarily be forced

00:14:07.950 --> 00:14:10.920
into some interpretation.

00:14:10.920 --> 00:14:13.860
We're just going to solve the
planning problem directly.

00:14:13.860 --> 00:14:19.470
So somehow or other, a
household is assigned.

00:14:19.470 --> 00:14:24.320
Household j is assigned capital
and is operating project type

00:14:24.320 --> 00:14:25.360
i.

00:14:25.360 --> 00:14:28.340
And this is the
net rate of return.

00:14:28.340 --> 00:14:31.780
Notice that we allow
individuals to vary

00:14:31.780 --> 00:14:33.640
in their rates of return.

00:14:33.640 --> 00:14:35.860
The planner could
take advantage if it

00:14:35.860 --> 00:14:38.740
knows that some people are
better than other people

00:14:38.740 --> 00:14:39.620
at doing things.

00:14:39.620 --> 00:14:41.680
So we're not just
getting rid of talent.

00:14:41.680 --> 00:14:47.600
We're embedding it at some
level in these rates of return.

00:14:47.600 --> 00:14:57.203
And then they have basically
the tree and the fruit.

00:14:57.203 --> 00:14:58.370
That's their starting point.

00:14:58.370 --> 00:15:01.730
And then they get taxes
and transfers, these Taus.

00:15:01.730 --> 00:15:05.210
I mean, here it's written
positive as if it's incoming

00:15:05.210 --> 00:15:08.180
and adds to the resources
of the household.

00:15:08.180 --> 00:15:12.350
But in fact, like a
risk sharing group

00:15:12.350 --> 00:15:18.480
you can give and get and
contribute to the social fund.

00:15:18.480 --> 00:15:24.380
So the planning problem
is to maximize discounted

00:15:24.380 --> 00:15:26.390
weighted expected utility.

00:15:26.390 --> 00:15:29.300
So these Lambda j weights
are the pareto weights

00:15:29.300 --> 00:15:32.090
for households type j.

00:15:32.090 --> 00:15:35.780
They're not necessarily the
same over all the households.

00:15:35.780 --> 00:15:39.860
And this whole term here
is the utility function,

00:15:39.860 --> 00:15:46.660
which as noted, is just
the return on the trees

00:15:46.660 --> 00:15:50.240
plus these transfers.

00:15:50.240 --> 00:15:58.240
And then discounted
expected return for tomorrow

00:15:58.240 --> 00:15:59.900
I usually write as Beta.

00:15:59.900 --> 00:16:04.160
But anyway, it's an
intertemporal discount rate.

00:16:04.160 --> 00:16:06.640
And so you have the
value function today

00:16:06.640 --> 00:16:12.140
given wealth today and expected
value of wealth tomorrow w

00:16:12.140 --> 00:16:13.550
prime.

00:16:13.550 --> 00:16:17.170
And wealth today
can be allocated

00:16:17.170 --> 00:16:20.830
into basically consumption.

00:16:20.830 --> 00:16:23.770
So this is just
summing over not only

00:16:23.770 --> 00:16:27.640
over all projects for household
j, but all households j.

00:16:27.640 --> 00:16:31.270
So this is again,
just consumption.

00:16:31.270 --> 00:16:35.620
So consumption plus
capital allocated tomorrow

00:16:35.620 --> 00:16:41.380
equals total wealth, pretty
standard kind of growth market

00:16:41.380 --> 00:16:42.442
structure.

00:16:46.380 --> 00:16:50.670
And what is total
wealth of the economy?

00:16:50.670 --> 00:16:53.580
It's basically not only
the fruit of the trees,

00:16:53.580 --> 00:16:54.990
but the trees themselves.

00:16:57.970 --> 00:17:00.470
So you can take this expression
and put it on the right hand

00:17:00.470 --> 00:17:02.870
side if you want.

00:17:02.870 --> 00:17:04.609
Because they have
pre-existing capital.

00:17:04.609 --> 00:17:06.710
They have the rate
of return on that.

00:17:06.710 --> 00:17:08.540
You've got total
resources available.

00:17:08.540 --> 00:17:10.940
You can allocate
it to consumption

00:17:10.940 --> 00:17:14.950
or set some aside to continue
the capital stock for tomorrow.

00:17:20.160 --> 00:17:22.380
And so we just substitute
in the expressions

00:17:22.380 --> 00:17:31.330
for tomorrow's wealth and
today's wealth for that matter.

00:17:31.330 --> 00:17:35.280
And then this odd
looking thing here

00:17:35.280 --> 00:17:37.980
is just a substitution
from the previous equation.

00:17:37.980 --> 00:17:41.640
But there's a common
term on both sides.

00:17:41.640 --> 00:17:43.110
That's why it looks
kind of weird.

00:17:43.110 --> 00:17:48.600
Because this is really 1
plus r times k over here.

00:17:48.600 --> 00:17:51.090
But there's also a 1
plus r times k here.

00:17:51.090 --> 00:17:53.580
And the rk things
are canceling out.

00:17:53.580 --> 00:17:58.680
So this is just
straightforward algebra.

00:17:58.680 --> 00:18:01.560
So we're going to
maximize this thing

00:18:01.560 --> 00:18:06.120
by choosing the transfer as
Tau j and the assignments

00:18:06.120 --> 00:18:07.560
of tomorrow's capital stock.

00:18:10.512 --> 00:18:12.972
AUDIENCE: Was there
supposed to be uncertainty?

00:18:12.972 --> 00:18:15.440
It's just their
return on capital?

00:18:15.440 --> 00:18:17.930
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:18:17.930 --> 00:18:21.226
Yeah, there's no
preference shocks here.

00:18:21.226 --> 00:18:23.138
AUDIENCE: What's the
process [INAUDIBLE]??

00:18:23.138 --> 00:18:24.530
[INAUDIBLE]

00:18:24.530 --> 00:18:26.612
PROFESSOR: Don't
have to specify yet.

00:18:26.612 --> 00:18:28.090
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:18:28.090 --> 00:18:30.290
PROFESSOR: That's
probably a good thing.

00:18:30.290 --> 00:18:36.800
OK, so if you looked, we've
actually seen this before.

00:18:36.800 --> 00:18:40.700
But it's explicit here again.

00:18:40.700 --> 00:18:43.970
Consumption and capital
are interrelated through

00:18:43.970 --> 00:18:45.170
this resource constraint.

00:18:45.170 --> 00:18:48.890
So when you take a derivative
to maximize with respect

00:18:48.890 --> 00:18:52.250
to the transfers, you'll
pick up a derivative

00:18:52.250 --> 00:18:54.560
in the utility function.

00:18:54.560 --> 00:18:57.590
And the sum of total
transfers is down here

00:18:57.590 --> 00:18:58.750
in the resource constraint.

00:18:58.750 --> 00:19:01.150
And there's a Lagrange
multiplier in front of it,

00:19:01.150 --> 00:19:01.910
right?

00:19:01.910 --> 00:19:03.650
So you're going to
get margin weighted,

00:19:03.650 --> 00:19:06.110
margin utility of
consumption today

00:19:06.110 --> 00:19:08.265
equal to a Lagrange multiplier.

00:19:08.265 --> 00:19:09.890
And when you
differentiate with respect

00:19:09.890 --> 00:19:15.120
to the choice of tomorrow's
capital stock k prime,

00:19:15.120 --> 00:19:17.280
well, that's going to
enter in tomorrow's value.

00:19:17.280 --> 00:19:20.940
So you'll have a derivative
of the value function

00:19:20.940 --> 00:19:25.690
and then internally this
sort of rate of return.

00:19:25.690 --> 00:19:32.540
And this prime thing is also
entering into the same resource

00:19:32.540 --> 00:19:33.040
constraint.

00:19:33.040 --> 00:19:34.707
So you're going to
get the same Lagrange

00:19:34.707 --> 00:19:39.140
multiplier as on consumption.

00:19:39.140 --> 00:19:43.480
So here is a summary
of those words.

00:19:43.480 --> 00:19:46.060
Weighted margin
utilities are equated

00:19:46.060 --> 00:19:50.290
across all the households to a
common contemporaneous Lagrange

00:19:50.290 --> 00:19:52.030
multiplier.

00:19:52.030 --> 00:19:55.930
And then this is kind of a--

00:19:55.930 --> 00:20:01.450
it's an exactly Euler equation
for capital accumulation.

00:20:01.450 --> 00:20:04.510
This is the price
of capital today.

00:20:04.510 --> 00:20:06.410
It's how much consumption
you're giving up.

00:20:06.410 --> 00:20:09.340
And this is expected
discounted value

00:20:09.340 --> 00:20:11.350
of having capital tomorrow.

00:20:11.350 --> 00:20:13.810
It's the derivative
of the value function

00:20:13.810 --> 00:20:16.180
times the rate of
return, depending

00:20:16.180 --> 00:20:19.450
on which project i
and J is being chosen.

00:20:19.450 --> 00:20:25.550
Note that this is for every
project, every capital stock

00:20:25.550 --> 00:20:28.220
of type i for household j.

00:20:31.426 --> 00:20:34.850
Now, so far I've talked
about real assets.

00:20:34.850 --> 00:20:37.790
But it's not too hard.

00:20:37.790 --> 00:20:41.330
And we do actually allow
external borrowing.

00:20:41.330 --> 00:20:45.710
You could imagine a village
is able to borrow in land.

00:20:45.710 --> 00:20:48.590
Or the whole set
of four villages

00:20:48.590 --> 00:20:52.260
have some relationship with the
rest of the external economy.

00:20:52.260 --> 00:20:56.040
That still leaves
this sub problem.

00:20:56.040 --> 00:20:59.030
I mean, throwing
these things in might

00:20:59.030 --> 00:21:01.370
deliver some extra conditions
that we're ignoring.

00:21:01.370 --> 00:21:03.787
But what we're doing is not
inconsistent with having

00:21:03.787 --> 00:21:04.370
this equation.

00:21:07.880 --> 00:21:14.330
All right, so if you
just take this one

00:21:14.330 --> 00:21:21.245
and divide both sides
through by Mu, you get this.

00:21:27.410 --> 00:21:29.710
And then you take the
expectation operator

00:21:29.710 --> 00:21:31.690
in front of everything,
including Mu,

00:21:31.690 --> 00:21:36.470
even though it's not random
from the point of day t.

00:21:36.470 --> 00:21:41.510
And then you can
rewrite this guy here

00:21:41.510 --> 00:21:46.040
as something called m or m
prime, since in effect it's

00:21:46.040 --> 00:21:47.840
for tomorrow.

00:21:47.840 --> 00:21:55.520
And this r prime ij is
basically capital R is little r.

00:21:55.520 --> 00:21:58.040
One plus r is sort of
the gross rate of return.

00:22:00.910 --> 00:22:05.550
So this is hopefully
not mysterious.

00:22:05.550 --> 00:22:09.000
It's just basically a
relabeling of variables.

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:11.930
And it's like the
Euler equation.

00:22:11.930 --> 00:22:14.720
But if you want to
impress your friends

00:22:14.720 --> 00:22:17.510
and bewilder your enemies,
you call this thing

00:22:17.510 --> 00:22:21.580
the stochastic discount factor.

00:22:21.580 --> 00:22:25.860
But all it is is the
way society as a whole

00:22:25.860 --> 00:22:27.360
is discounting the future.

00:22:27.360 --> 00:22:33.310
It's tomorrow's sort of shadow
price of resources relative

00:22:33.310 --> 00:22:35.040
to today's.

00:22:35.040 --> 00:22:37.800
So you're discounting tomorrow.

00:22:37.800 --> 00:22:39.960
And it's random.

00:22:39.960 --> 00:22:41.820
Because these rates
of return are random.

00:22:41.820 --> 00:22:45.090
And so the amount of resources
available in the economy

00:22:45.090 --> 00:22:46.290
is likely random.

00:22:46.290 --> 00:22:47.490
So it's stochastic.

00:22:53.160 --> 00:22:55.260
There's a danger in
talking to someone

00:22:55.260 --> 00:22:57.060
about stochastic
discount factors.

00:22:57.060 --> 00:23:00.980
Because the conversation
will keep going.

00:23:00.980 --> 00:23:03.720
And you may learn more
or get bewildered.

00:23:03.720 --> 00:23:07.230
But anyway, as promised,
we'll keep track of this.

00:23:13.690 --> 00:23:18.540
So it's true for all
households, all sectors.

00:23:18.540 --> 00:23:22.427
And the finance
jargon is we just

00:23:22.427 --> 00:23:24.010
looked at something
called the pricing

00:23:24.010 --> 00:23:27.850
equation in the consumption
based asset pricing world.

00:23:27.850 --> 00:23:30.850
But for us it's just an
Euler equation holding

00:23:30.850 --> 00:23:34.300
at say the village or let's
call it township level.

00:23:38.600 --> 00:23:42.740
Another thing you may or may not
know or remember from finance

00:23:42.740 --> 00:23:46.280
is you can take assets
and bundle them.

00:23:46.280 --> 00:23:48.110
So you can have a
particular asset

00:23:48.110 --> 00:23:51.410
held by a particular
household, a project.

00:23:51.410 --> 00:23:54.650
Or you could take a
collection of assets.

00:23:54.650 --> 00:23:58.670
That Euler equation has to
hold for any asset individually

00:23:58.670 --> 00:24:00.320
and all assets collectively.

00:24:00.320 --> 00:24:03.890
You can bundle, package,
rebundle anyway you want.

00:24:03.890 --> 00:24:07.140
And anything that's
actually held--

00:24:07.140 --> 00:24:12.960
by the way, there's sort of
out of equilibrium projects

00:24:12.960 --> 00:24:14.850
we're not seeing.

00:24:14.850 --> 00:24:19.290
They wouldn't satisfy
the Euler equation.

00:24:19.290 --> 00:24:22.170
They have a low rate of return
relative to the other ones.

00:24:22.170 --> 00:24:24.060
So we're only seeing
these equilibrium ones

00:24:24.060 --> 00:24:26.310
that the households
actually hold.

00:24:26.310 --> 00:24:30.000
And of course, we're looking at
the data at what they actually

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:32.530
hold.

00:24:32.530 --> 00:24:35.630
I'm mentioning this
bundling because--

00:24:35.630 --> 00:24:38.070
and you'll see it again.

00:24:38.070 --> 00:24:41.790
But we might as well get
our minds around it here.

00:24:41.790 --> 00:24:45.030
We are going to look at a
household's rate of return.

00:24:45.030 --> 00:24:47.700
And typical households, as you
know, you've already seen this,

00:24:47.700 --> 00:24:50.610
are doing more than one thing.

00:24:50.610 --> 00:24:54.240
Some of the incoming money
is from labor supply.

00:24:54.240 --> 00:24:56.550
They have crops,
maybe multiple crops.

00:24:56.550 --> 00:25:01.800
Some of them have both that
and a business and so on.

00:25:01.800 --> 00:25:06.540
We try very hard to assign
these assets individually

00:25:06.540 --> 00:25:08.340
to particular activities.

00:25:08.340 --> 00:25:09.660
But it's kind of treacherous.

00:25:09.660 --> 00:25:11.700
And we're likely
to make mistakes.

00:25:11.700 --> 00:25:13.800
What do you do with a
pickup truck for example?

00:25:13.800 --> 00:25:16.260
Is that just used in farming?

00:25:16.260 --> 00:25:17.860
Or they're going to the bank.

00:25:17.860 --> 00:25:20.070
They're taking the
kids to school.

00:25:20.070 --> 00:25:22.770
And so rather than
face all of that

00:25:22.770 --> 00:25:26.350
we just aggregate up
over all the activities

00:25:26.350 --> 00:25:29.460
any particular household
is doing and call that

00:25:29.460 --> 00:25:30.750
a collection of assets.

00:25:30.750 --> 00:25:34.460
And the Euler
equation should apply.

00:25:34.460 --> 00:25:36.330
Now, remember a little
bit of your sort

00:25:36.330 --> 00:25:44.670
of econometrics with means
and variances or easy mistakes

00:25:44.670 --> 00:25:45.810
to make.

00:25:45.810 --> 00:25:48.000
The expectation of
two random variables

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:53.250
is not just the product
of the expectations.

00:25:53.250 --> 00:25:56.540
You've got to adjust
for the covariance,

00:25:56.540 --> 00:25:59.180
unless this happens to be zero.

00:25:59.180 --> 00:26:02.270
But this covariance is
going to be crucial for us.

00:26:02.270 --> 00:26:07.700
Because you can see already
it's the covariance between dare

00:26:07.700 --> 00:26:10.010
I say it, the stochastic
discount factor,

00:26:10.010 --> 00:26:14.060
which reflects the community's
relative valuation of resources

00:26:14.060 --> 00:26:20.390
and the particular return on
project i held by household j.

00:26:20.390 --> 00:26:27.460
So since we already had
this equal to 1 as the Euler

00:26:27.460 --> 00:26:30.820
equation, right?

00:26:30.820 --> 00:26:36.190
So now we just substitute
this stuff into here.

00:26:36.190 --> 00:26:38.130
And we get this.

00:26:38.130 --> 00:26:42.690
And you could basically divide
through by the expectation

00:26:42.690 --> 00:26:45.450
of m prime.

00:26:45.450 --> 00:26:49.470
You're going to get 1 over
that here, get rid of it here.

00:26:49.470 --> 00:26:53.010
Get the covariance
divided by it here.

00:26:53.010 --> 00:26:55.050
And then you divide
and multiply,

00:26:55.050 --> 00:26:57.810
which doesn't do any
harm, by the variance

00:26:57.810 --> 00:27:01.800
of m prime and rearrange terms.

00:27:01.800 --> 00:27:06.100
So you get this thing.

00:27:06.100 --> 00:27:08.180
So we're finally
arriving at something

00:27:08.180 --> 00:27:14.520
close to what we want, which
is the expected rate of return,

00:27:14.520 --> 00:27:15.980
which is going to
be in the data,

00:27:15.980 --> 00:27:19.980
the average return for household
j over all the time periods.

00:27:19.980 --> 00:27:20.480
Not quite.

00:27:23.520 --> 00:27:25.920
It sort of looks like
a linear function,

00:27:25.920 --> 00:27:30.810
something with an intercept,
and then Beta Lambda.

00:27:30.810 --> 00:27:36.030
Beta, and finance guys talk
about betas all the time.

00:27:36.030 --> 00:27:40.530
Beta for us just means sort
of the normalized covariance

00:27:40.530 --> 00:27:47.710
between the returns on ij
and the stochastic discount

00:27:47.710 --> 00:27:51.030
factor, which I already
pointed to above.

00:27:51.030 --> 00:27:53.080
It's normalized by
the overall variance.

00:27:56.320 --> 00:27:58.060
So that's kind of
the risk factor,

00:27:58.060 --> 00:28:00.810
or the quantity of risk.

00:28:00.810 --> 00:28:06.440
And this other thing could
be called the price of risk.

00:28:06.440 --> 00:28:08.210
But it's nothing
other than this.

00:28:08.210 --> 00:28:10.190
It's the variance
divided by the mean.

00:28:14.920 --> 00:28:19.560
It almost looks like a
coefficient of variation,

00:28:19.560 --> 00:28:23.669
like Sigma squared divided
by Mu or something.

00:28:29.420 --> 00:28:30.800
And there's a name for it.

00:28:30.800 --> 00:28:35.280
And I'll tell you what
it is in a second.

00:28:35.280 --> 00:28:38.000
All right, so this is
what I said already.

00:28:38.000 --> 00:28:43.280
Quantities, prices--
oh, and one more thing.

00:28:43.280 --> 00:28:46.490
What was that intercept?

00:28:46.490 --> 00:28:49.460
Well basically,
let's just define

00:28:49.460 --> 00:28:52.760
this thing, this Gamma,
well, it was already

00:28:52.760 --> 00:28:56.420
defined to be 1 over the
expectation of m prime.

00:28:56.420 --> 00:28:59.215
But let's call it
the risk free return.

00:29:04.090 --> 00:29:07.470
First of all, why
is there no risk?

00:29:07.470 --> 00:29:10.080
Because all the
variability in the economy

00:29:10.080 --> 00:29:16.290
is in m prime or the one that
we care about for that equation.

00:29:16.290 --> 00:29:18.250
And we've already
taken the expectation.

00:29:18.250 --> 00:29:19.920
So there's nothing random left.

00:29:19.920 --> 00:29:21.910
So this is a number.

00:29:21.910 --> 00:29:25.360
It's not something stochastic.

00:29:25.360 --> 00:29:26.440
It should be obvious.

00:29:26.440 --> 00:29:30.220
But I always do it myself, which
is take that to be an asset,

00:29:30.220 --> 00:29:33.940
plug that back into the
asset Euler equation

00:29:33.940 --> 00:29:36.850
that we already have and
thus convince yourself

00:29:36.850 --> 00:29:40.690
that that equation applies
for the risk free return.

00:29:40.690 --> 00:29:45.610
And you'll get this
right back again, OK?

00:29:49.560 --> 00:29:53.190
So anyway, the point is risk
free because the covariance

00:29:53.190 --> 00:29:57.030
of this risk free rate with
m prime is 0 by construction.

00:30:16.390 --> 00:30:21.660
So let's just look
at this again.

00:30:21.660 --> 00:30:27.940
This is the rate of return
of the mean, or average, rate

00:30:27.940 --> 00:30:30.940
of return on project ij.

00:30:30.940 --> 00:30:32.900
Subtract off the risk free rate.

00:30:32.900 --> 00:30:34.450
This is the return differential.

00:30:34.450 --> 00:30:37.540
This is how much the--

00:30:37.540 --> 00:30:41.800
in finance, it would be
like the junk bond premium

00:30:41.800 --> 00:30:43.120
over and above treasuries.

00:30:45.770 --> 00:30:50.490
And so that difference
is sort of the premium

00:30:50.490 --> 00:30:55.050
that you get for
holding a risky asset.

00:30:55.050 --> 00:30:59.790
And it's linearly
related to the covariance

00:30:59.790 --> 00:31:01.280
of that asset with the market.

00:31:06.090 --> 00:31:08.400
So again, I'm going back
and forth a bit more

00:31:08.400 --> 00:31:09.870
with this finance language.

00:31:09.870 --> 00:31:12.300
But it's just all right
off the Euler equation.

00:31:12.300 --> 00:31:19.320
This is just standard
sort of manipulation.

00:31:19.320 --> 00:31:24.750
So we can even make
it more obvious

00:31:24.750 --> 00:31:28.800
if you're wondering
what m prime really is.

00:31:28.800 --> 00:31:32.340
Let's go with quadratic utility.

00:31:32.340 --> 00:31:34.856
So this is the form of it.

00:31:34.856 --> 00:31:40.060
The community's value function
as a function of wealth

00:31:40.060 --> 00:31:44.560
is just basically the squared
of the difference between wealth

00:31:44.560 --> 00:31:51.680
and some subsistence level with
a coefficient in front of it.

00:31:51.680 --> 00:31:54.230
So of course, if you
take the derivative of it

00:31:54.230 --> 00:31:58.340
with respect to w
the twos cancel out.

00:31:58.340 --> 00:32:01.640
And you get eta times this
difference, which is linear,

00:32:01.640 --> 00:32:02.570
by the way.

00:32:02.570 --> 00:32:04.250
That's huge.

00:32:04.250 --> 00:32:09.350
So marginal value of
wealth is linear in wealth.

00:32:09.350 --> 00:32:12.380
That's what you
get at a quadratic.

00:32:12.380 --> 00:32:16.150
And then you just substitute
our expression for w

00:32:16.150 --> 00:32:22.570
prime tomorrow into
that expression

00:32:22.570 --> 00:32:25.770
and do a little relabeling.

00:32:25.770 --> 00:32:28.560
So all of a sudden, this
looks like the return

00:32:28.560 --> 00:32:35.390
on the village average and the
village average capital stock.

00:32:35.390 --> 00:32:37.460
OK, the village
average capital stock

00:32:37.460 --> 00:32:40.580
is the sum of the
capital stocks allocated

00:32:40.580 --> 00:32:43.040
over all the projects
and all the households,

00:32:43.040 --> 00:32:47.120
as it should be to
be in total, right?

00:32:47.120 --> 00:32:50.300
And then what is the
rate of return on it?

00:32:50.300 --> 00:32:56.090
Well basically, it's like
a capital weighted return.

00:32:56.090 --> 00:32:59.720
So the total return
is coming from a bunch

00:32:59.720 --> 00:33:01.130
of individual projects.

00:33:01.130 --> 00:33:04.760
So you just take the return
on all the individual projects

00:33:04.760 --> 00:33:07.130
but weight them by the
capital being allocated

00:33:07.130 --> 00:33:09.680
to those projects
and renormalize

00:33:09.680 --> 00:33:11.930
by the total capital stock.

00:33:11.930 --> 00:33:14.645
So it's a portfolio
weighted return.

00:33:17.760 --> 00:33:19.800
That's just a definition.

00:33:19.800 --> 00:33:22.840
But of course, then
it looks like this.

00:33:22.840 --> 00:33:26.440
And you take this up
here and this here.

