01:05:43.280 --> 01:05:45.245
to the overall variance.

01:05:45.245 --> 01:05:48.530
So now, we have this
measure, finally.

01:05:48.530 --> 01:05:52.100
But note that it didn't just
come from using the data.

01:05:52.100 --> 01:05:54.590
We used the structure of
the model to back it out.

01:06:01.600 --> 01:06:09.180
And that idiosyncratic part
is large, at least half

01:06:09.180 --> 01:06:11.590
and in many instances.

01:06:11.590 --> 01:06:14.200
Substantially more
than half of the risk

01:06:14.200 --> 01:06:17.110
is due to the idiosyncratic
component, rather than

01:06:17.110 --> 01:06:17.970
the aggregate.

01:06:17.970 --> 01:06:20.360
Now, one word of caution.

01:06:20.360 --> 01:06:23.230
We still haven't
rejected the model.

01:06:23.230 --> 01:06:27.490
No one in finance says there
aren't idiosyncratic returns.

01:06:27.490 --> 01:06:29.800
The question is
whether they're priced.

01:06:29.800 --> 01:06:33.850
If you believe in the capital
asset model or the consumption

01:06:33.850 --> 01:06:38.350
based risk sharing model,
then idiosyncratic returns

01:06:38.350 --> 01:06:38.860
can exist.

01:06:38.860 --> 01:06:40.120
But they're completely pooled.

01:06:43.070 --> 01:06:45.710
So this per se does
not reject the model.

01:06:45.710 --> 01:06:51.500
But when we now
stick the variance,

01:06:51.500 --> 01:06:57.060
sigma j, into the
benchmark model.

01:06:57.060 --> 01:07:02.210
And we're still doing
OK with aggregate risk.

01:07:02.210 --> 01:07:04.110
But here's the
rejection, if you like.

01:07:04.110 --> 01:07:07.260
The idiosyncratic
risk is positively

01:07:07.260 --> 01:07:09.590
associated with
expected rate of return

01:07:09.590 --> 01:07:12.370
and for all the households.

01:07:12.370 --> 01:07:19.450
Now, this is the if you
like, the disappointing part,

01:07:19.450 --> 01:07:22.390
or the tension, which
is you go to all

01:07:22.390 --> 01:07:25.030
this work with a benchmark.

01:07:25.030 --> 01:07:26.710
And it seems to be
doing really well.

01:07:26.710 --> 01:07:32.380
But there are features
of the data against which

01:07:32.380 --> 01:07:33.400
it's not doing well.

01:07:37.090 --> 01:07:41.620
So it's clear that it's not
an entirely perfect markets

01:07:41.620 --> 01:07:44.860
world from the point of
view of the rate of return

01:07:44.860 --> 01:07:47.470
of these assets.

01:07:47.470 --> 01:07:49.570
But is the glass half
empty or half full?

01:07:49.570 --> 01:07:53.080
Because it's also true
that a substantial amount

01:07:53.080 --> 01:07:55.600
of the rates of return had
to do with market risk.

01:07:55.600 --> 01:07:58.590
And most development
researchers would

01:07:58.590 --> 01:08:00.030
have ignored that market part.

01:08:00.030 --> 01:08:02.820
I think it's fair to
say, even though it's

01:08:02.820 --> 01:08:05.160
kind of a natural
corollary to risk sharing.

01:08:19.540 --> 01:08:21.099
So let's go back
to these alphas.

01:08:26.029 --> 01:08:29.290
So Jensen talks about having
portfolio managers who

01:08:29.290 --> 01:08:32.630
are somehow smarter
or better than others.

01:08:32.630 --> 01:08:34.665
And they have abnormal returns.

01:08:34.665 --> 01:08:35.540
I mean, I don't know.

01:08:35.540 --> 01:08:37.359
This is kind of
hard for economists.

01:08:37.359 --> 01:08:42.380
It's like, well, if you do
so well, why don't everyone

01:08:42.380 --> 01:08:43.580
just go in there?

01:08:43.580 --> 01:08:46.590
Like, I never make money.

01:08:46.590 --> 01:08:47.960
I don't trust my instincts.

01:08:47.960 --> 01:08:54.890
But I'll tell you
story about Walmart.

01:08:54.890 --> 01:08:59.330
So one of my colleagues who
was at Chicago, a sociologist,

01:08:59.330 --> 01:09:00.450
was in Arkansas.

01:09:00.450 --> 01:09:06.420
And he saw this big square flat
building in northern Arkansas.

01:09:06.420 --> 01:09:09.029
And he sort of checked
it out and said,

01:09:09.029 --> 01:09:11.470
well, this is a really
novel way of doing business.

01:09:11.470 --> 01:09:14.175
Well, it turned out to be
practically the first branch

01:09:14.175 --> 01:09:14.675
of Walmart.

01:09:14.675 --> 01:09:15.769
And he bought stock.

01:09:18.290 --> 01:09:22.069
He did quite well obviously.

01:09:22.069 --> 01:09:24.952
Anyway, so maybe some
portfolio managers

01:09:24.952 --> 01:09:25.910
are better than others.

01:09:25.910 --> 01:09:30.300
Maybe some households are
somehow better than others.

01:09:30.300 --> 01:09:39.080
And we've now got a way of
adjusting for all those risk

01:09:39.080 --> 01:09:44.270
factors, both the idiosyncratic
and the aggregate.

01:09:44.270 --> 01:09:46.970
By the way, you will
be relieved a bit

01:09:46.970 --> 01:09:49.910
maybe to know that
when we rank order

01:09:49.910 --> 01:09:52.490
the households by the
unadjusted rates of return

01:09:52.490 --> 01:09:54.680
and the risk adjusted
rates of return,

01:09:54.680 --> 01:09:58.280
the ordering is
largely preserved.

01:09:58.280 --> 01:10:00.590
But the orders of
magnitude are not.

01:10:00.590 --> 01:10:03.140
The second point is
it's not just completely

01:10:03.140 --> 01:10:06.920
downshifting the distribution
after you subtract stuff off.

01:10:06.920 --> 01:10:08.180
The tails come in.

01:10:08.180 --> 01:10:10.760
So it has a different
level of skewness.

01:10:10.760 --> 01:10:14.840
So it's kind of a serious
filter on the data.

01:10:14.840 --> 01:10:19.820
But some of the earlier
results that poor households

01:10:19.820 --> 01:10:22.775
have high rates of return and
reinvest in their own projects,

01:10:22.775 --> 01:10:23.900
we're going to rerun those.

01:10:23.900 --> 01:10:28.130
But we're pretty confident those
kind of results don't go away.

01:10:28.130 --> 01:10:30.665
And I haven't misled you
in the earlier lectures.

01:10:33.720 --> 01:10:39.690
So finally, here is running
these regressions, where

01:10:39.690 --> 01:10:43.950
we have aggregate risk,
also allow idiosyncratic

01:10:43.950 --> 01:10:51.120
risk, where we have the betas
on aggregate physical capital

01:10:51.120 --> 01:10:53.560
and the coefficients on sigma.

01:10:53.560 --> 01:11:04.050
So the first two slides I
said households who are older

01:11:04.050 --> 01:11:06.420
take on less risk,
which means basically,

01:11:06.420 --> 01:11:08.550
both the idiosyncratic
and aggregate risk

01:11:08.550 --> 01:11:11.050
factors are negative.

01:11:11.050 --> 01:11:15.990
You might be willing to tell
a demographic story for that.

01:11:15.990 --> 01:11:18.130
We don't really have it
embedded in the model.

01:11:18.130 --> 01:11:23.750
It's more like a residual or
behavioral thing at this point.

01:11:23.750 --> 01:11:27.740
Because these residuals
aren't supposed to be there.

01:11:27.740 --> 01:11:32.950
And here is basically the
wealth again, negative.

01:11:32.950 --> 01:11:40.450
So poor people have higher
correlation of their activities

01:11:40.450 --> 01:11:42.650
with a village average.

01:11:42.650 --> 01:11:45.215
And the residual have a
higher residual variance.

01:11:47.765 --> 01:11:49.990
I'm going to come back to that.

01:11:49.990 --> 01:11:52.350
Poor people seem to be
exposed to a lot of risk.

01:11:57.870 --> 01:12:04.470
However, if you take out both
sources of risk and regress

01:12:04.470 --> 01:12:07.260
on demographics and
all these things,

01:12:07.260 --> 01:12:10.050
wealth finally goes positive.

01:12:10.050 --> 01:12:17.970
And also, this is a dummy for
male, so to speak, is negative.

01:12:17.970 --> 01:12:22.590
So that the female headed
households and the high wealth

01:12:22.590 --> 01:12:25.950
households are the households
with the highest sort

01:12:25.950 --> 01:12:27.380
of residual rates of return.

01:12:33.300 --> 01:12:40.350
OK, so now what I don't have
in front of me unfortunately,

01:12:40.350 --> 01:12:42.750
we didn't quite
get close enough.

01:12:42.750 --> 01:12:45.960
But you may remember that
QJE paper from lecture one

01:12:45.960 --> 01:12:50.250
on volatility, growth,
finance, what's related?

01:12:50.250 --> 01:12:52.860
And we said, well, we've
got to look at sectors.

01:12:52.860 --> 01:12:55.710
We've got to figure out how
much each sector is contributing

01:12:55.710 --> 01:12:59.280
to overall change
in value added.

01:12:59.280 --> 01:13:01.460
And there was some really
cool decomposition.

01:13:01.460 --> 01:13:05.650
So we're running that
on these Thai data.

01:13:05.650 --> 01:13:12.430
So we can see at
the level of income

01:13:12.430 --> 01:13:14.420
how diversified are
these households?

01:13:14.420 --> 01:13:20.390
It's similar, but not identical
to this CAPM type approach.

01:13:20.390 --> 01:13:22.930
And so far at least, we're
getting the same answer,

01:13:22.930 --> 01:13:28.330
that it's the relatively poor
households who are specialized.

01:13:28.330 --> 01:13:30.090
And the things
they specialize in

01:13:30.090 --> 01:13:38.300
have high volatility, and so on.

01:13:38.300 --> 01:13:41.360
So poor people seem
to be exposed to risk

01:13:41.360 --> 01:13:42.740
at least on the income side.

01:13:47.220 --> 01:13:57.560
So here's moving to Sweden,
more sort of standard asset

01:13:57.560 --> 01:14:02.310
stuff, which John
Campbell and co-authors

01:14:02.310 --> 01:14:05.580
have done called Down or Out.

01:14:05.580 --> 01:14:11.780
And what they're trying
to do is very similar.

01:14:11.780 --> 01:14:15.170
They're trying to look
at household management

01:14:15.170 --> 01:14:18.890
of financial affairs
using measurement

01:14:18.890 --> 01:14:22.760
in this amazing Swedish data.

01:14:22.760 --> 01:14:25.580
Sweden is a socialist
country largely.

01:14:25.580 --> 01:14:27.080
And they measure everything.

01:14:27.080 --> 01:14:31.160
And everyone has a common
ID, and your whole portfolio,

01:14:31.160 --> 01:14:32.810
labor supply, everything.

01:14:35.790 --> 01:14:38.720
So I've been
collaborating a little bit

01:14:38.720 --> 01:14:45.190
with a Riksbank largely
influenced by this paper.

01:14:45.190 --> 01:14:48.550
Now unfortunately, it takes
us away from development.

01:14:48.550 --> 01:14:49.690
That's not my point.

01:14:49.690 --> 01:14:51.680
My point is the commonality.

01:14:51.680 --> 01:14:53.680
They're going to look at
mean variance frontiers

01:14:53.680 --> 01:14:56.080
and see what
households are doing.

01:14:56.080 --> 01:14:59.770
In particular, what are the poor
people doing or the rich ones?

01:15:03.080 --> 01:15:04.790
The focus is a bit
different, which is

01:15:04.790 --> 01:15:07.560
households can make mistakes.

01:15:07.560 --> 01:15:13.400
In other words, let's just
assume the model is right.

01:15:13.400 --> 01:15:15.680
And the mean
variance frontier is

01:15:15.680 --> 01:15:19.460
what it is and then see
households in the interior who

01:15:19.460 --> 01:15:21.538
could get less variance
or a higher mean

01:15:21.538 --> 01:15:22.955
if they only move
to the frontier.

01:15:25.560 --> 01:15:27.450
And then they look
by characteristics,

01:15:27.450 --> 01:15:29.340
like education,
wealth, and so on

01:15:29.340 --> 01:15:35.130
to see who is
under diversified--

01:15:35.130 --> 01:15:37.480
those are the down people--

01:15:37.480 --> 01:15:40.360
and who's not participating
as in the stock market.

01:15:40.360 --> 01:15:42.840
Those are the out people.

01:15:42.840 --> 01:15:47.190
And hence the title, very
clever, Down and Out.

01:15:47.190 --> 01:15:51.820
And they measure the welfare
costs of those deviations.

01:15:51.820 --> 01:15:53.450
As I said, they
have amazing data.

01:15:53.450 --> 01:15:59.440
And here you can see sort of how
households manage their growth

01:15:59.440 --> 01:16:01.720
wealth in Sweden.

01:16:01.720 --> 01:16:03.160
This is the cash.

01:16:03.160 --> 01:16:03.910
Oh, look at that.

01:16:03.910 --> 01:16:07.780
Poor people have a lot of cash.

01:16:07.780 --> 01:16:10.000
I think cash just doesn't
mean Swedish krona.

01:16:10.000 --> 01:16:13.035
I think it also
means bank accounts.

01:16:17.480 --> 01:16:19.980
But stocks, poor people
don't hold stocks.

01:16:23.200 --> 01:16:26.350
Mutual fund has this
funny hunch-- now,

01:16:26.350 --> 01:16:29.860
it's interesting that
this is real estate.

01:16:29.860 --> 01:16:33.430
So this is both financial
as well as real.

01:16:33.430 --> 01:16:37.340
And on a household side,
there are some businesses here

01:16:37.340 --> 01:16:37.840
actually.

01:16:37.840 --> 01:16:43.520
But most of these households
are salary employees.

01:16:43.520 --> 01:16:45.660
But they can hold
durable goods in housing.

01:16:45.660 --> 01:16:50.750
If you take the physical
housing wealth out of it,

01:16:50.750 --> 01:16:52.895
then the cash thing
is still going down.

01:16:56.290 --> 01:16:59.410
The mutual funds is largely
flat, except at the very low

01:16:59.410 --> 01:17:00.160
and the high end.

01:17:00.160 --> 01:17:02.380
And then you see this stock.

01:17:05.350 --> 01:17:08.880
It's the 90 percentile
up are the people who

01:17:08.880 --> 01:17:13.690
have reasonably substantial
holdings in the stocks.

01:17:13.690 --> 01:17:17.650
I ask myself these
questions a lot in Thailand.

01:17:17.650 --> 01:17:21.960
Sort of maybe they
shouldn't be investing

01:17:21.960 --> 01:17:22.890
in their own projects.

01:17:22.890 --> 01:17:27.510
Maybe they should be investing
in Bangkok money market

01:17:27.510 --> 01:17:31.520
funds, safe funds.

01:17:31.520 --> 01:17:33.950
We should be sort of looking
at the whole mean variance

01:17:33.950 --> 01:17:36.100
frontier for these.

01:17:36.100 --> 01:17:37.420
And we are asking them now.

01:17:37.420 --> 01:17:38.605
We're actively involved.

01:17:38.605 --> 01:17:41.150
I was on the phone
again last night.

01:17:41.150 --> 01:17:45.800
We're about to be asking them
a bunch of questions about,

01:17:45.800 --> 01:17:47.370
are they aware of other assets?

01:17:50.150 --> 01:17:53.540
But in Sweden the point that
Campbell is going to make

01:17:53.540 --> 01:18:02.180
is you've got those categories.

01:18:02.180 --> 01:18:06.050
And households can make mistakes
by picking volatile assets,

01:18:06.050 --> 01:18:09.380
holding a concentrated
portfolio, picking correlated.

01:18:09.380 --> 01:18:11.930
See the parallel here
with what I was saying

01:18:11.930 --> 01:18:17.630
happens in the Thai villages in
terms of relatively poor people

01:18:17.630 --> 01:18:19.910
not being diversified
and for some reason

01:18:19.910 --> 01:18:20.960
doing riskier things.

01:18:24.400 --> 01:18:26.080
Or if you go in
the stock market,

01:18:26.080 --> 01:18:28.035
you could pick your own stocks.

01:18:28.035 --> 01:18:30.400
It's not a particularly
clever thing to do.

01:18:34.210 --> 01:18:36.280
And this is the picture
that makes the paper.

01:18:40.570 --> 01:18:42.960
So here's the sort
of mean variance

01:18:42.960 --> 01:18:46.140
frontier, standard
deviation in means.

01:18:46.140 --> 01:18:49.630
Here's where they ought to be.

01:18:49.630 --> 01:18:52.210
Adjusting or not for
international asset holdings,

01:18:52.210 --> 01:18:52.840
that's another.

01:18:52.840 --> 01:18:54.790
They do both.

01:18:54.790 --> 01:19:01.880
But they're basically saying,
small guys in some sense

01:19:01.880 --> 01:19:03.950
are unsophisticated
and cautious.

01:19:03.950 --> 01:19:05.720
They're pretty far
off the frontier.

01:19:05.720 --> 01:19:09.320
But they don't have
kind of a lot to lose.

01:19:09.320 --> 01:19:17.390
And these richer guys up here,
they're more sophisticated.

01:19:17.390 --> 01:19:20.840
Their line is quote unquote
above this brown one.

01:19:20.840 --> 01:19:22.190
But their gap is huge.

01:19:22.190 --> 01:19:25.330
So I'll spare you the details.

01:19:25.330 --> 01:19:27.350
They're actually measuring
the welfare loss.

01:19:27.350 --> 01:19:30.050
And some of these
richer households are--

01:19:30.050 --> 01:19:33.410
because they are not
diversifying-- actually

01:19:33.410 --> 01:19:36.740
have fairly substantial
welfare losses.

01:19:36.740 --> 01:19:42.020
Now, John goes behavioral in
this and maybe rightly so.

01:19:42.020 --> 01:19:47.270
He's saying should we really
be telling households in Brazil

01:19:47.270 --> 01:19:50.450
about investing in
whatever is [INAUDIBLE]..

01:19:50.450 --> 01:19:53.480
I can't remember the acronym.

01:19:53.480 --> 01:19:55.010
Or are they going
to make mistakes

01:19:55.010 --> 01:19:57.500
and they're better
off not knowing?

01:19:57.500 --> 01:19:58.430
There was a question.

01:19:58.430 --> 01:20:00.430
AUDIENCE: This is already
answered by the model,

01:20:00.430 --> 01:20:02.830
but this is welfare.

01:20:02.830 --> 01:20:05.510
This takes into account the
marginal utility of wealth.

01:20:05.510 --> 01:20:07.790
PROFESSOR: Yeah, actually,
I'm sparing you a lot.

01:20:07.790 --> 01:20:08.570
Oh, I should say.

01:20:08.570 --> 01:20:10.617
This is on the reading list.

01:20:10.617 --> 01:20:12.200
But I knew I wasn't
going to have time

01:20:12.200 --> 01:20:13.820
to cover it in much detail.

01:20:13.820 --> 01:20:16.070
So I picked like six slides.

01:20:16.070 --> 01:20:19.160
But I'll post the whole paper.

01:20:19.160 --> 01:20:21.200
If you're interested,
you don't necessarily

01:20:21.200 --> 01:20:23.975
want to or have time to
read the whole paper.

01:20:23.975 --> 01:20:25.850
You might as well look
at these lecture notes

01:20:25.850 --> 01:20:28.110
that I created previously.

01:20:28.110 --> 01:20:32.200
And the same thing
for this paper,

01:20:32.200 --> 01:20:36.220
which is [INAUDIBLE] with
[INAUDIBLE],, Dynamic Risk

01:20:36.220 --> 01:20:36.720
Management.

01:20:36.720 --> 01:20:38.160
I've only got a few slides.

01:20:38.160 --> 01:20:40.630
I think I'm going to jump
and show you something.

01:20:43.210 --> 01:20:44.190
Fly Southwest.

01:20:46.790 --> 01:20:48.630
So this guy's
loading that airplane

01:20:48.630 --> 01:20:51.720
that capital stock up with
this variable input, the fuel.

01:20:54.760 --> 01:20:58.290
They buy forward positions.

01:20:58.290 --> 01:21:02.480
Because the price of
gasoline moves around a lot.

01:21:02.480 --> 01:21:06.710
So they basically
buy forward, OK?

01:21:06.710 --> 01:21:11.640
They commit now to buy gasoline
at a pegged future price.

01:21:11.640 --> 01:21:14.150
Now, what happens if the spot
price is lower than that?

01:21:14.150 --> 01:21:16.010
It's like, oh, darn.

01:21:16.010 --> 01:21:17.870
We should've waited.

01:21:17.870 --> 01:21:19.910
Actually, you could
renege on that contract.

01:21:22.680 --> 01:21:24.690
And so what do they
do with those things?

01:21:24.690 --> 01:21:30.950
You've got to post collateral
against these forward gasoline

01:21:30.950 --> 01:21:31.450
hedges.

01:21:34.190 --> 01:21:36.210
Where are we going with this?

01:21:36.210 --> 01:21:40.490
We're going to get to sort
of thinking about something

01:21:40.490 --> 01:21:47.100
that Chris [INAUDIBLE] was
doing in Ghana, which is,

01:21:47.100 --> 01:21:55.370
do you want to use your scarce
collateral to borrow and get

01:21:55.370 --> 01:22:00.290
more aircraft with potentially
high rate of return?

01:22:00.290 --> 01:22:02.480
Or do you want to use
your scarce collateral

01:22:02.480 --> 01:22:05.750
and tie it up hedging
against future states

01:22:05.750 --> 01:22:08.260
of the world s prime?

01:22:08.260 --> 01:22:13.260
And this paper is about how in
practice this may not happen.

01:22:13.260 --> 01:22:15.280
Now, when does it happen?

01:22:19.900 --> 01:22:21.690
Where is it?

01:22:21.690 --> 01:22:26.320
It happens when the airline
isn't doing very well.

01:22:26.320 --> 01:22:32.110
